article.headline: MVP-less Spurs hold their own

images.name: Horry Robert 031106 195x262
images.caption: Robert Horry had 12 points for the stubborn Spurs.

article.linkText: Lakers put away Spurs in double overtime thriller
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Somebody check the calendar and make sure it's still November. It certainly seemed like playoff time as the Lakers and Spurs went at each other for more than 3½ hours. Los Angeles remained undefeated Thursday night, though it took massive efforts from Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal to get the Lakers past injury-ravaged San Antonio 120-117 in double overtime. Bryant scored 37 and took an embarrassing fall in the third quarter, while O'Neal had 35 points, 20 rebounds, six assists and four blocked shots as Los Angeles improved the league's best record to 5-0. San Antonio was without injured starters Tim Duncan and Tony Parker, yet the defending champions played an inspired game and got a career-high 33 points along with 12 rebounds and seven assists from Manu Ginobili. "It would have been the best (game of his NBA career) by far if I had made one more shot," Ginobili said. "I bet nobody in the arena thought we were going to win it." Five others reached double figures for the Spurs to push the game into two extra periods before it finally ended with O'Neal blocking Kevin Willis' 3-point attempt. With most fans standing to watch the final moments of the fourth quarter and much of the two overtimes, the nationally televised game was riveting theater in a matchup of two of the West's biggest rivals. San Antonio ousted the Lakers from the playoffs last spring and ended their three-year run as champions, and this was the Spurs' chance to put the first blemish on the retooled Lakers' record. Despite being so short-handed, they nearly did. Bryant shot 16-for-29 and added five rebounds and four steals, while O'Neal was 12-for-23 from the field and 11-for-16 at the foul line. His two free throws with 16.9 seconds left broke the last of 16 ties. Karl Malone added 15 points and 19 rebounds before fouling out, while Gary Payton had 16 points, seven rebounds and six assists. "It was just one game in a long season, just another game," Bryant said. "When it really counts will be in the playoffs." Four players -- Malone, Devean George, Malik Rose and Rasho Nesterovic -- fouled out. The fans booed Bryant every time he touched the ball, and Bryant went out of his way to respond. On the Lakers' first possession of the second half, Bryant abandoned any semblance of a set offense and went to work one-on-one against defensive specialist Bruce Bowen. Dribbling and changing directions rapidly, Bryant freed himself for a 20-foot jumper that dropped through. But while he backpedalled downcourt and waved his finger back and forth in a gesture to the crowd, Bryant's feet got tangled up and he tripped and fell on his backside. He uprighted himself with a backward somersault. "He played hard, but right now he's not quick enough to guard Ginobili," Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. "I thought he got better as the game went on." The final 24 seconds of regulation included a missed 7-foot jumper by Bryant, a missed drive by Ginobili that was altered by O'Neal's outstretched arm, and an off-target 20-footer by Malone just before the final buzzer. Neither team led by more than two in the first overtime, which Bryant and Ginobili each had a chance to end with a game-winner. Bryant's shot, however, missed from 18 feet and Ginobili misfired on a similar shot off an inbounds play with seven-tenths of a second left. The Lakers took a 117-112 lead in the second overtime, but ex-Laker Robert Horry made two free throws and a 3-pointer to tie it. Bryant missed a shot with 36 seconds left, another with 25 seconds remaining and another with 18 ticks left, but Los Angeles grabbed offensive rebounds each time. O'Neal was fouled after the third one and made both shots for a 119-117 lead. Ginobili then missed a leaner from 6 feet and Willis missed a tip-in, but the Spurs got one more chance when Payton made just one of two from the line with 4 seconds left. With Ginobili the first option and Hedo Turkoglu the second, San Antonio's inbounds pass went to Willis. The Lakers seemed surprised that Horry, who hit so many clutch 3-pointers for them in recent years, did not get the ball for the final shot. "He wasn't open," said Jason Hart, who inbounded the ball on the final play.

Game notes
Ginobili's previous career high was 20 points. ... Duncan will not return until the middle of next week at the earliest. Parker will practice Friday to test his left ankle, and the soonest date for his return is Monday against Utah. ... All five Lakers starters reached double figures in their first five games, but George was held to six points to break that streak. ... O'Neal got to re-attempt three foul shots because of lane violations. He also committed one of his own.
